<paragraph blockId="12.[136,1452,1742,2092]" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis box="[136,214,1742,1768]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Shrubs</emphasis>
or small trees, 
<quantity box="[393,466,1742,1768]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="m" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3 m</quantity>
tall. 
<emphasis box="[526,632,1742,1768]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Branches</emphasis>
green, cylindrical, costate. 
<emphasis box="[948,1026,1743,1768]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Leaves</emphasis>
opposite, sessile, discolorous, blades 1.8–2.4 × 
<quantity box="[246,352,1778,1805]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.15" metricValueMax="7.3" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="6.15" valueMax="7.3" valueMin="5.0">5–7.3 cm</quantity>
, obovate, coriaceous, glabrous, attenuate at base, emarginate at apex, entire at margin. 
<emphasis box="[1302,1452,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Inflorescence</emphasis>
in terminal cymes, 9–10-flowered, peduncle ca. 
<quantity box="[676,756,1814,1840]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="0.6">0.6 cm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis box="[766,858,1814,1840]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Flowers</emphasis>
homostylous, 6-merous, pedicel 
<quantity box="[1230,1310,1814,1841]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="4.5">4.5 cm</quantity>
; calyx 2–2.2 × 
<quantity box="[158,284,1850,1877]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.8 cm</quantity>
, yellowish, winged, not keeled, campanulate, glabrous. Corolla greenish yellow, campanulate, tube 1.1–2 × 
<quantity box="[158,237,1886,1912]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="1.6">1.6 cm</quantity>
, lobes 1–0.8 × 
<quantity box="[404,483,1886,1912]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="0.4">0.4 cm</quantity>
, at base obovate, at apex angulate; stamens 
<quantity box="[969,1097,1886,1912]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8499999999999999" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="1.8499999999999999" valueMax="2.8" valueMin="0.9">0.9–2.8 cm</quantity>
, isodynamous, adnate, conation 
<quantity box="[136,215,1922,1948]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="1.3">1.3 cm</quantity>
, anthers basifixed; ovary 8 × 
<quantity box="[546,613,1922,1948]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
, style 
<quantity box="[685,813,1922,1949]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="0.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" unit="cm" value="1.45" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="0.4">0.4–2.5 cm</quantity>
, stigma bilobed. 
<emphasis box="[1003,1061,1923,1948]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Fruit</emphasis>
septicidal capsule.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="74" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[136,1452,1742,2092]" lastBlockId="13.[136,1452,158,545]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="74" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,490,1957,1984]" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Habitat and distribution</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martius" authorityYear="1827" box="[526,727,1959,1984]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" genus="Prepusa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis box="[526,727,1959,1984]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Prepusa montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species of its genus occurring in the Cerrado and “campo rupestre” of 
<collectingRegion box="[368,436,1994,2020]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Bahia</collectingRegion>
, is considered as endemic (
<bibRefCitation author="Siqueira, G. B. &amp; Espirito Santo, F. B. &amp; Rapini, A." box="[737,958,1994,2020]" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref17510" refString="Siqueira, G. B., Espirito Santo, F. B. &amp; Rapini, A. (2014) Flora da Bahia: Gentianaceae. Sitientibus serie Ciencias Biologicas 14: 1 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.13102 / scb 295" type="journal article" year="2014">
Siqueira 
<emphasis box="[838,893,1994,2020]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Calio, M. F. A. &amp; Guimaraes, E. F. &amp; Saavedra, M. M. &amp; Melo, A." box="[969,1155,1994,2021]" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" refId="ref12841" refString="Calio, M. F. A., Guimaraes, E. F., Saavedra, M. M. &amp; Melo, A. (2015) Gentianaceae. Lista de Especies da Flora do Brasil. Jardim Botanico do Rio de Janeiro. Available from: http: // floradobrasil. jbrj. gov. br / jabot / floradobrasil / FB 117 (accessed 7 January 2019)" type="url" year="2015">
Calió 
<emphasis box="[1035,1091,1994,2020]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
) and restricted to Chapada 
<taxonomicName box="[136,267,2030,2056]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Podostemaceae" genus="Diamantina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="12" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Diamantina</taxonomicName>
(Calió 2009, 
<bibRefCitation author="Siqueira, G. B. &amp; Espirito Santo, F. B. &amp; Rapini, A." box="[415,631,2030,2056]" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref17510" refString="Siqueira, G. B., Espirito Santo, F. B. &amp; Rapini, A. (2014) Flora da Bahia: Gentianaceae. Sitientibus serie Ciencias Biologicas 14: 1 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.13102 / scb 295" type="journal article" year="2014">
Siqueira 
<emphasis box="[514,569,2030,2056]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
) in the cities of Andaraí, Lençóis, Morro do Chapéu and Mucugê (
<bibRefCitation author="Siqueira, G. B. &amp; Espirito Santo, F. B. &amp; Rapini, A." pageId="12" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref17510" refString="Siqueira, G. B., Espirito Santo, F. B. &amp; Rapini, A. (2014) Flora da Bahia: Gentianaceae. Sitientibus serie Ciencias Biologicas 14: 1 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.13102 / scb 295" type="journal article" year="2014">
Siqueira 
<emphasis box="[136,194,2066,2092]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, it is also considered one of the rare species in 
<collectingCountry box="[955,1023,2066,2092]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="73">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Calio, M. F. A. &amp; Guimaraes, E. F." box="[1040,1333,2066,2092]" pageId="12" pageNumber="73" pagination="185 - 186" refId="ref12762" refString="Calio, M. F. A. &amp; Guimaraes, E. F. (2009) Gentianaceae. In: Giulietti, A. M., Rapini, A., Andrade, M. J. G., Queiroz, L. P. &amp; Silva, J. M. C. (Eds.) Plantas raras do Brasil. Conservacao Internacional, Belo Horizonte. pp. 185 - 186." type="book chapter" year="2009">Calió &amp; Guimarães 2009</bibRefCitation>
). It is also classified, according to risk categories of the Red List of Endangered Species (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN &amp; Cambridge U. K." box="[1032,1171,158,184]" pageId="13" pageNumber="74" refId="ref15757" refString="IUCN (2020) The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, version 2020 - 1. IUCN Red List Unit, Cambridge U. K. Available from: http: // www. iucnredlist. org / (accessed 19 May 2020)" type="url" year="2020">IUCN 2020</bibRefCitation>
), as a vulnerable species (VU) (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN &amp; Cambridge U. K." box="[210,347,194,220]" pageId="13" pageNumber="74" refId="ref15757" refString="IUCN (2020) The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, version 2020 - 1. IUCN Red List Unit, Cambridge U. K. Available from: http: // www. iucnredlist. org / (accessed 19 May 2020)" type="url" year="2020">IUCN 2020</bibRefCitation>
, CNCFlora 2014a, 
<bibRefCitation author="Guimaraes, EF &amp; Queiroz, GA &amp; Negrao, R. &amp; Hering, R. &amp; Amaro, R. &amp; Serrano, T." box="[565,819,194,220]" pageId="13" pageNumber="74" pagination="141 - 144" refId="ref15214" refString="Guimaraes, EF., Queiroz, GA., Negrao, R., Hering, R., Amaro, R. &amp; Serrano, T. (2014) Gentianaceae. In: Martinelli, G., Messina, T. &amp; Santos Filho, L. (Eds.) Livro Vermelho da Flora do Brasil: Plantas raras do Cerrado. Instituto de Pesquisa Jardim Botanico do Rio de Janeiro, Rio de Janeiro, pp. 141 - 144." type="book chapter" year="2014">
Guimarães 
<emphasis box="[694,750,194,220]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="74">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). In the present work, the distribution modeling analysis corroborates this distribution restricted to the Chapada 
<taxonomicName box="[772,903,230,256]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Podostemaceae" genus="Diamantina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="13" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Diamantina</taxonomicName>
areas, with a greater suitability to the Chapada areas and allowing inferences to be extrapolated only to nearby locations, such as, for example, Catolés and Pico das Almas, compared in this study (
<figureCitation box="[500,566,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1815,1837]" captionTargetBox="[168,1421,200,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[151,1436,187,1788]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Parque Municipal de Mucugê—Projeto Sempre Viva (PMM), Bahia, Brazil. Map of the study area, evidencing the location of PMM and other areas of the Espinhaço Range (ER) used for comparison in this study (A), “campo rupestre” phytophysiognomy (B). Photo B by Ariane Leite. Legend: (Lilac area) ER above 1000 m a.s.l." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5424487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5424487/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="74">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[580,666,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1661,1683]" captionTargetBox="[444,1147,867,1622]" captionTargetId="figure-307@7.[434,1153,857,1637]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Maps of occurrence with localities used for the species distribution modeling, showing the study area location within South America. Curtia diffusa (A), Macrocarpaea illecebrosa (B), Prepusa montana (C), Schultesia bahiensis (D), Schultesia crenuliflora (E), Schultesia minensis (F), Schultesia pachyphylla (G)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5424489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5424489/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="74">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[678,763,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[136,229,1736,1758]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,190,1712]" captionTargetId="figure-19@11.[340,1247,190,1712]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Species of Gentianaceae from the Parque Municipal de Mucugê - Projeto Sempre Viva (PMM), Bahia, Brazil: Calolisianthus pedunculatus (A), Chelonanthus purpurascens (B), Curtia verticillaris (C), Curtia tenuifolia (D), Prepusa montana (E), Schultesia bahiensis (F), Schultesia crenuliflora (G), Schultesia pachyphylla (H). Scale bars:A: 2 cm; B: 1 cm; C: 0,5 cm; D: 0,5 cm; E: 2 cm; F–H: 1 cm. Photo A, B, E, F, G and H by Maria Luiza Silveira de Carvalho; C and D by Vinicius Dittrich and Gustavo Shimizu, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5424491" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5424491/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="74">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[775,861,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="15.[136,229,1180,1202]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1155]" captionTargetId="figure-19@15.[151,1436,190,1155]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 4. Maps of environmental suitability of native/endemic species of Gentianaceae in the Espinhaço Range (ER): Curtia diffusa (A), Macrocarpaea illecebrosa (B), Prepusa montana (C), Schultesia bahiensis (D), Schultesia crenuliflora (E), Schultesia minensis (F), Schultesia pachyphylla (G)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5424493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5424493/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="74">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
, Appendix 1).
</paragraph>
